## Decisions settled, and details left to the spec-author

Most of the questions this document raised in the previous cycle have
now been **settled by the operator**, and the prose above has been
updated to match. Recorded here so the resolutions are not lost:

- **Detector name.** Settled: the element is **Detector (D)** — no
  "photo detector", no separate analyzer (a polarizer is a polarizer
  wherever it sits; §9).
- **R1 axis.** Settled: **R1 turns around the element's surface normal
  (N1)**; it coincides with the central ray only at normal incidence,
  and parts company with the CR once R2 ≠ 0 (§7.3).
- **Ctrl + wheel.** Settled: **Ctrl + wheel zooms** (honouring the OS
  convention); **R2 moves to Ctrl + Shift + wheel** (§10).
- **Ribbon tab set.** Settled as a **starting point** (Build / Element /
  Trace-View / Experiment / Settings; §1).
- **Side-ray count.** Settled: **one CR plus eight side rays**, a 45°
  circle at normal incidence, with a **show-CR-only / show-all** toggle
  (§8).
- **Storage of groups and collections.** Settled: a **separate JSON
  file** (§11).

A few **details remain for the spec-author** — these are refinements,
not open operator decisions, and none blocks a first draft:

- **Schematic drawing weights.** Exact line thicknesses, colours, and
  the on-screen offset of the eight side rays, chosen from established
  optics-diagram practice for good visibility (§8).
- **Schematic element thickness and reflection drawing.** How thick a
  schematic element is drawn and how reflected and transmitted groups
  are shown together when both are on (§8).
- **Default box dimensions.** Concrete defaults for the A × A × B boxes
  by role (thin-wide optical element, long-narrow source; §7.1).
- **Mapping the separate groups/collections JSON** onto the beam-tree
  and the per-project file (§11–§12) — user-facing behaviour is fixed
  above; the internal mapping is the spec-author's.

